{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "09 — Recall & Search",
  "description": "How Balaur finds relevant knowledge for each conversation turn: the two-tier context injection policy, the recallTerms heuristic, the FTS5 sidecar index lifecycle (boot rebuild, record hooks, disposability), the shared searchActiveNodes skeleton behind both memory recall and cross-type search, and the LIKE fallback that keeps recall live even without the index.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/knowledge/context.go",
      "line": 12,
      "title": "9.1 — Two-tier injection policy",
      "description": "```\n// tier 1 (upfront): active memories with importance >= 4, capped.\n//   The things the companion should never forget: who you are, hard\n//   constraints, standing preferences.\n// tier 2 (recall): active memories matching the current user message,\n//   capped. Cheap LIKE relevance today; the seam stays put when FTS5 or\n//   embeddings land.\n```\n\nEvery turn pays two costs:\n- **Tier 1 (always-paid, upfront):** up to 12 active memories with `importance >= 4`. The importance pips on each memory card (1–5) are the owner's direct control over this budget — a pip-4 memory is always in context; a pip-2 memory only appears if recalled.\n- **Tier 2 (per-message, recall):** up to 6 active memories that match the current message. Cost is proportional to relevance — irrelevant turns pay nothing for the recall slot.\n\nSkills are never injected into the prompt body: only `name + when_to_use` lines appear, and the `skill` tool loads the full content on demand. This keeps prompts inspectable and token budgets under owner control.\n\nSee `BuildContext` (line 32 in this file) for how these two tiers are assembled."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/knowledge/context.go",
      "line": 32,
      "title": "9.2 — BuildContext: assembling the knowledge block",
      "description": "```go\nfunc BuildContext(app core.App, userMessage string) (string, []*core.Record) {\n    upfront, err := UpfrontMemories(app, upfrontLimit)\n    ...\n    recalled, err := SearchActive(app, recallTerms(userMessage), recallLimit)\n    ...\n    skills, err := ActiveSkills(app)\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n`BuildContext` is called once per turn by the shared turn pipeline (`internal/turn`). It returns two things: the Markdown block appended to the system prompt, and the list of records injected — so the caller can `Touch` them to update their `last_used` timestamp.\n\nThe three sections (upfront memories, recalled memories, skill index lines) are written in order. The `seen` map deduplicates: a high-importance memory that is also recalled for the current message is only rendered once, in the upfront section.\n\nThis function is the sole seam between the knowledge package and the turn pipeline. Tour 05 covers the turn pipeline that calls it."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/knowledge/context.go",
      "line": 87,
      "title": "9.3 — recallTerms: cheapest possible relevance",
      "description": "```go\nfunc recallTerms(msg string) []string {\n    words := strings.FieldsFunc(strings.ToLower(msg), func(r rune) bool {\n        return !((r >= 'a' && r <= 'z') || (r >= '0' && r <= '9') || r >= 0x80)\n    })\n    // deduplicate, keep words >= 4 chars, sort longest first, keep top 3\n}\n```\n\n`recallTerms` reduces a chat message to its 3 longest distinct words (>=4 characters). The assumption: longer words are more topically specific and pair well with both LIKE matching and FTS5 token matching.\n\nThis is deliberately a proxy, not a real relevance model. The comment says so: \"Replaced wholesale when real ranking lands; callers won't notice.\" The function is unexported — changing it is an internal decision that does not affect the `BuildContext` API.\n\nThe 4-character minimum filters out stop words (`the`, `and`, `for`) without maintaining a stop-word list. Unicode characters above `0x80` pass through — non-ASCII words are welcome."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/knowledge/search.go",
      "line": 76,
      "title": "9.4 — SearchActive: memory-scoped FTS5 + LIKE fallback",
      "description": "```go\nfunc SearchActive(app core.App, terms []string, limit int) ([]*core.Record, error) {\n    return searchActiveNodes(app, terms, limit,\n        func(ix *search.Index) ([]string, error) {\n            return ix.QueryKind(terms, string(Memory), limit)\n        },\n        func(r *core.Record) (*core.Record, bool) { ... },\n        func() ([]*core.Record, error) { /* LIKE fallback */ ... },\n    )\n}\n```\n\n`SearchActive` is the recall entry point from `BuildContext`. It is memory-scoped: even though the FTS5 index covers all node types, `QueryKind` narrows the query to `kind = 'memory'`.\n\nThe three closures passed to `searchActiveNodes` define:\n- **query:** which FTS method to call (kind-narrowed for memories)\n- **keep:** whether a returned record should be included (active status + correct type)\n- **fallback:** the LIKE scan over `nodes` filtered to `type = 'memory'`, sorted by importance descending\n\nSee `searchActiveNodes` (line 30 in this file) for the shared skeleton."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/knowledge/search.go",
      "line": 30,
      "title": "9.5 — searchActiveNodes: the shared FTS5-or-fallback skeleton",
      "description": "```go\nfunc searchActiveNodes(\n    app core.App, terms []string, limit int,\n    query    func(ix *search.Index) ([]string, error),\n    keep     func(r *core.Record) (*core.Record, bool),\n    fallback func() ([]*core.Record, error),\n) ([]*core.Record, error) {\n    // FTS5 fast path\n    if raw, ok := app.Store().GetOk(search.StoreKey); ok { ... }\n    // fallback\n    return fallback()\n}\n```\n\nBoth `SearchActive` (memory recall) and `SearchAllActive` (cross-type search) share this skeleton. The caller injects the three strategy closures; the skeleton owns the FTS path mechanics:\n\n1. Read the `*search.Index` singleton from `app.Store()` — absent if the index failed to open at boot.\n2. Run `query(ix)` to get bm25-ranked node IDs.\n3. Hydrate via `app.FindRecordsByIds(\"nodes\", ids)` and filter with `keep`.\n4. Re-sort survivors by FTS rank order (since `FindRecordsByIds` returns unordered).\n5. If FTS yields nothing, call `fallback`.\n\nThe LIKE path runs whenever the index is unavailable — when no `*search.Index` is stored under `StoreKey` because the open-and-rebuild failed twice at boot (see step 9.9). It is not a degraded mode: it is the original deterministic implementation that recall always had. (Deleting `pb_data/search.db` does not strand you on LIKE — `Open` recreates the table and the next boot rebuilds the index; the file is disposable, not load-bearing.)"
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/search/index.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "9.6 — The FTS5 sidecar index",
      "description": "```go\n// Package search provides the FTS5 knowledge recall index — a rebuildable\n// sidecar SQLite database backed by the ncruces/go-sqlite3 wazero driver\n// (CGO-free, FTS5 included). It indexes all active node types (note, memory,\n// skill, day, and typed objects), keyed by kind.\n```\n\n`pb_data/search.db` is a **separate SQLite database** from PocketBase's `pb_data/data.db`. It holds one FTS5 virtual table:\n\n```sql\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS knowledge_fts\nUSING fts5(id UNINDEXED, kind UNINDEXED, title, content, extra)\n```\n\nWhy a separate database? PocketBase's default SQLite driver (`modernc.org/sqlite`) does not ship with FTS5. The `ncruces/go-sqlite3` driver (WASM-based, CGO-free) does include FTS5 — but it must be registered as a separate `database/sql` driver. Running both drivers against the same database file would be unsafe.\n\nThe `ncruces` driver uses wazero (WebAssembly runtime in Go) — no C compiler, no LLVM, no platform-specific build requirements. The WASM SQLite binary is embedded in the Go binary.\n\nThe index is **disposable**: rebuilt from PocketBase data on boot and kept eventually consistent via record hooks. Deleting it is always safe. The `kind` column enables `QueryKind` to narrow results to a single node type without a separate table per type."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/search/index.go",
      "line": 54,
      "title": "9.7 — Rebuild: idempotent boot operation",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (ix *Index) Rebuild(app core.App) error {\n    tx, err := ix.db.Begin()\n    if _, err := tx.Exec(`DELETE FROM knowledge_fts`); err != nil { ... }\n    recs, err := app.FindRecordsByFilter(\"nodes\", \"status = 'active'\", ...)\n    stmt, _ := tx.Prepare(`INSERT INTO knowledge_fts(id, kind, title, content, extra) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)`)\n    for _, r := range recs {\n        stmt.Exec(r.Id, r.GetString(\"type\"), r.GetString(\"title\"), r.GetString(\"body\"), nodeExtra(r))\n    }\n    return tx.Commit()\n}\n```\n\n`Rebuild` is idempotent: it deletes all rows and refills from the current active nodes across **all node types** (note, memory, skill, day, objects). Safe to run on boot even after a partial write (crash mid-rebuild). The entire rebuild runs in one transaction — no partial state is ever visible.\n\nThe `extra` column carries type-specific searchable text. For `memory` nodes it holds `when_to_use` (the recall hint); other types contribute nothing extra yet. This preserves parity with the prior memory-only index while the cross-type search capability is new."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/search/index.go",
      "line": 176,
      "title": "9.8 — Query and QueryKind: bm25-ranked retrieval",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (ix *Index) Query(terms []string, limit int) ([]string, error) {\n    rows, err := ix.db.Query(\n        `SELECT id FROM knowledge_fts WHERE knowledge_fts MATCH ? ORDER BY rank LIMIT ?`,\n        matchExpr(terms), limit,\n    )\n    ...\n}\n\nfunc (ix *Index) QueryKind(terms []string, kind string, limit int) ([]string, error) {\n    rows, err := ix.db.Query(\n        `SELECT id FROM knowledge_fts WHERE knowledge_fts MATCH ? AND kind = ? ORDER BY rank LIMIT ?`,\n        matchExpr(terms), kind, limit,\n    )\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nFTS5's `rank` column is a bm25 score (negative — smaller is better). `ORDER BY rank` returns the most relevant nodes first.\n\n`matchExpr` (line 147) wraps each term in double-quotes so FTS5 treats it as a literal string token, not an operator. Embedded double-quotes in a term are escaped by doubling per FTS5 spec §3.1 — user text cannot inject query operators.\n\n- **`Query`**: cross-type, any kind. Backs `SearchAllActive`.\n- **`QueryKind`**: narrows to one node kind (e.g. `\"memory\"`). Backs `SearchActive` so recall does not surface notes or skills as if they were memories.\n\nBoth return a list of **node IDs**, not records. `searchActiveNodes` then fetches the full records from PocketBase."
    },
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 226,
      "title": "9.9 — registerSearchIndex: boot + hooks",
      "description": "```go\nfunc registerSearchIndex(app core.App) {\n    dbPath := filepath.Join(app.DataDir(), \"search.db\")\n\n    openAndRebuild := func() (*search.Index, error) { ... }\n\n    ix, err := openAndRebuild()\n    if err != nil {\n        // Corrupt or unreadable — delete and retry once.\n        os.Remove(dbPath)\n        ix, err = openAndRebuild()\n        if err != nil { return } // LIKE fallback active\n    }\n\n    app.Store().Set(search.StoreKey, ix)\n\n    app.OnRecordAfterCreateSuccess(\"nodes\").BindFunc(upsertHook)\n    app.OnRecordAfterUpdateSuccess(\"nodes\").BindFunc(upsertHook)\n    app.OnRecordAfterDeleteSuccess(\"nodes\").BindFunc(deleteHook)\n}\n```\n\nThe lifecycle:\n1. **Open** the sidecar database (creates `search.db` if absent).\n2. **Rebuild** from all active nodes — full index from PocketBase.\n3. **Retry once** if the file was corrupt: delete and try again; if it fails a second time, log a warning and return without setting `StoreKey`. `searchActiveNodes` transparently uses the LIKE fallback.\n4. **Store** the `*Index` singleton in `app.Store()` under `search.StoreKey`.\n5. **Bind hooks** on the `nodes` collection (not `memories` — all node types are indexed): create/update → `Upsert`, delete → `Delete`. Hooks keep the index eventually consistent between boots.\n\nThe hooks re-read `StoreKey` on every invocation rather than closing over `ix` — this is safe because the index is never replaced after boot."
    }
  ]
}
